<TEXT>
merryle stanley rukeyser a pioneer of 
financial journalism who wrote columns for hearst newspapers and 
international news service for more than 30 years died wednesday at 
age 91 
rukeyser died at white plains hospital 
rukeyser also lectured and wrote nine books on financial 
subjects his sons louis and william became prominent economics 
journalists and ms bud rukeyser jr became a major television 
executive 
the chicagoborn rukeyser was raised in new york city and began 
his newspaper career at 17 while attending columbia university he 
worked summers as a reporter for the rockaway news and as assistant 
sports editor for the new york morning telegraph 
he joined the new york tribune in 1917 after his graduation and 
in 1920 at age 23 became the newspapers financial editor 
he moved to a similar post at the new york evening journal from 
1923 to 1926 and the following year began writing his financial 
columns for hearst and ins an assignment that lasted until 1957 
he also returned to columbia as a teacher in the school of 
journalism from 1918 to 1935 and as a student earning a masters 
degree in economics in 1925 
in 1958 he began a syndicated column everybodys money which 
he wrote for several years before cutting back on his work 
he continued to lecture at least once a year until a year ago 
said his son louis 
he called that his annual senility test to see if he could 
deliver a onehour lecture on economics without notes said louis 
rukeyser host of public televisions wall street week the 
senior rukeyser sometimes appeared on his sons television program 
most recently in november 1987 
rukeysers last book collective bargaining the power to 
destroy was published in 1968 
rukeysers first wife berenice did in 1964 after 24 years of 
marriage his second wife marjorie died in 1974 
survivors include four sons ms bud jr louis william 
and robert j 
</TEXT>
