a soviet woman who knew she carried the aids virus 
has been sentenced to four years in prison for defying doctors 
orders to refrain from sexual relations to avoid spreading the 
disease a newspaper reported 
the prison term given the 31yearold woman identified only as 
olga l by the newspaper socialist industry was believed to be 
the first under a tough government measure aimed at stopping the 
spread of aids 
the council of ministers in august 1987 warned soviets that 
infecting others with the virus would be punished as a crime and 
said anyone in the soviet union could be forced to take an aids 
antibody test 
socialist industry said in wednesdays report taht olga had been 
married to an african student and left with him for the congo after 
four years she returned to her homeland without a husband but 
with aids 
doctors discovered she was carrying the virus after she fell off 
a balcony at a restaurant in the southern ukraine city of kakhovka 
and took a routine blood sample when giving her first aid 
apparently olga though carrying the aids virus showed none of 
its symptoms a carrier of the disease is not yet sick but is 
capable of spreading the infection socialist industry noted 
olga was treated at a moscow clinic where on discharge doctors 
warned her no intimate relations the paper said 
but she paid no heed to these words the number of her partners 
even increased the newspaper said eight of them have already 
been identified and authorities are searching for more it said 
authorities orginally confined olga to kakhovka but she fled a 
local court then sentenced her to a fouryear prison term 
in september 1987 a suspected aids carrier from leningrad 
lyudmila l signed a pledge to refrain from sexual activity for 
five years if she reneges she risks a prison term of up to eight 
years soviet press acounts said at the time 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that 
damages the bodys immune system leaving victims susceptible to 
infections and cancer it is spread most often through sexual 
contact needles or syringes shared by drug abusers infected blood 
or blood products and from pregnant women to their offspring 
