<TEXT>
the jumbo jet that crashed wednesday in 
scotland had a maintenance history that included an onboard fire 
cracks and corrosion it was reported 
service records filed with the federal aviation administration 
show that since 1980 the boeing 747 experienced at least 24 
mechanical difficulties severe enough to warrant notation the los 
angeles times reported in thursdays edition 
in 1980 five reports were filed including one that cited a 
crack and one that cited failure of the plane to turn when it was on 
autopilot another difficulty involved a flameout of an engine 
during cruise flight the newspaper said 
reports in 1981 and 1983 cited numerous cracks in the planes 
floor beams and a floor beam web a 1984 report detailed fractures 
in exhaust casing rails and trailing edge flaps that were locked in 
place the times said 
the cause of wednesdays crash was not determined 
the pan am 747100 tail number n739pa was delivered to pan 
american in february 1970 it was the 15th 747 built the first 747 
ever delivered to an airline also pan am entered the fleet the 
previous month said david jimenez spokesman for boeing commercial 
airplanes which builds 747s in everett wash 
the plane that crashed had about 16500 cycles with one cycle 
being a takeoff and a landing jimenez said that however is not 
considered a particularly high number of cycles for a commercial 
jetliner he said a high number is considered to be more than 
50000 he said 
by comparison the aloha airlines boeing 737 that lost part of 
its fuselage during a flight over hawaii last april had more than 
89000 cycles a factor that was investigated in determining whether 
metal fatigue caused part of the fuselage to rip away 
boeing spokesman jack gamble said the plane that crashed was 
taken out of service between april 11 1987 and sept 27 1987 for 
substantial modification work and any structural deficiencies 
observed earlier would have been corrected then 
service difficulty reports filed in 1987 when the plane was out 
of service detailed corrosion and cracks the largest found near 
the upper part of the fuselage bulkhead measured 163 inches the 
times said a 22inch crack was found in a splice plate a joint 
area between metal parts the times said moderatetosevere 
corrosion also was found on those splice plates the times said 
other service difficulties cited in 1987 include a sheared nose 
gear bolt a missing pylon panel two instances of smoke in the 
passenger cabin and fire spewing from an engine pylon the newspaper 
said 
problems were reported after the plane was returned to service 
in october 1987 maintenance personnel responding to a boeing 
bulletin found severe corrosion at the rear bulkhead of the aircraft 
and severe corrosion on a portion of its fuselage the newspaper 
said 
a report in 1988 noted that a leading edge slat fell off the 
plane during takeoff from pakistan the newspaper said 
another boeing spokesman paul fang said the manufacturer would 
not release service records on any plane because once the 
airplanes are out of here theyre not our property anymore 
pan am spokesman jeff kriendler declined immediate comment on the 
report about the planes maintenance record 
pan am said in new york that the jetliner was part of the civil 
reserve air fleet a program to provide planes to the government in 
the event of national emergency 
fang later confirmed the plane was converted by boeing in 
wichita kan in 1987 to make it cargocapable in 48 hours for the 
national emergency program the air force pays for the modification 
but it was not able to convince most airlines to participate fang 
said so the conversion involving adding a cargo door and 
strengthening the floor was not a common procedure 
the federal aviation administrations mike monroney aeronautical 
center in oklahoma city has only two repair and alteration forms on 
file for the pan am plane a conveyance examiner who declined to 
give her name said such reports are not required and are sometimes 
submitted voluntarily by airlines 
