<TEXT>
the boeing 747 that crashed in scotland had 
been repaired for at least 21 mechanical difficulties since 1980 
including a small inboard fire and a large crack in an upper 
bulkhead according to federal records 
federal aviation administration service records show that in 
november 1987 a 163inch crack near the upper part of the fuselage 
bulkhead was discovered in the plane that crashed wednesday in 
scotland with 259 people aboard investigators today focused on 
terrorist threats to place a bomb on the jet and officials said 
sabotage seemed the most likely cause of the crash 
the faa report said the crack in the plane was corrosionrelated 
and corrosion was noted in the planes floor beam and other areas 
according to records filed march 25 a leading edge slat fell off 
the plane during takeoff from karachi pakistan and the slat 
section was found on the runway 
in october 1987 maintenance workers responding to a boeing 
service bulletin suggesting inspections of the plane and all similar 
aircraft found severe corrosion at the rear bulkhead and on part of 
the fuselage the report said 
a boeing spokesman said the plane was taken out of service last 
year for substantial modifications and any structural deficiencies 
observed earlier would have been corrected 
other service difficulties cited included a sheared nose gear 
bolt a missing pylon panel two instances of smoke in the passenger 
cabin and fire spewing from an engine pylon 
boeing commercial airplanes which builds the 747 in everett 
wash has no comment on the reports company spokesman craig martin 
said wednesday night and pan am spokesman jeff kriendler said he 
could not comment because he did not have the planes service 
history 
in washington faa spokeswoman joann sloane said there have been 
problems with minor cracks in 747s and the faa put out a directive 
to have the planes inspected 
but she said the inspections did not find much cracking those 
are certainly very reliable airplanes she said 
officials at pratt amp whitney in east hartford conn said they 
doubted their engines which powered the aircraft were responsible 
for the crash company investigators were dispatched to the accident 
scene 
the 747100 tail number n739pa was delivered to pan american 
world airways in february 1970 and was the 15th 747 built said 
david jimenez another boeing spokesman 
the plane had flown an estimated 72000 hours and about 16500 
cycles with one cycle being a takeoff and landing said boeings 
jack gamble jimenez said 50000 cycles is considered high for a 
commerical jetliner 
a pan am 747 was one of two jets involved in the worst disaster 
in commercial aviation history the march 27 1977 collision 
between two 747s at tenerife in the canary islands in which 582 
people died 
