<TEXT>
south africa signed an agreement thursday 
to end its 73year control of southwest africa and make the 
continents last colony the independent nation of namibia in 1990 
foreign minister rf botha put his signature on the accord at 
un headquarters along with the foreign ministers of cuba and 
angola which pledge to send home 50000 cuban troops stationed in 
angola 
by signing this agreement we have decided not to shoot it out 
we have decided to talk botha said it calls for a oneyear 
transition to namibian independence beginning april 1 
a year of usmediated negotiations led to the agreements 
secretary of state george p shultz un secretarygeneral javier 
perez de cuellar and other diplomats attended the signing 
missing from the ceremony was bernt carlsson un commissioner 
for namibia the 50yearold swedish diplomat was killed wednesday 
on the pan am jetliner that crashed in scotland 
shultz led the dignitaries in a minute of silence for carlsson 
after the signing ceremony shultz said the regional 
settlement concluded here today represents a momentous turning point 
in the history of southern africa with the independence of namibia 
africas last colonial question will have been resolved 
as the guns fall silent across the borders of southwestern 
africa the world will look to the nations of that vast region to 
turn to the resolution of their pressing internal matters through 
peaceful means he said referring to the civil war beween 
angolas marxist government and rebels supported by the united 
states and south africa 
the governments and individuals gathered in this place have 
truly given the world a special gift shultz declared 
angolan and southwest african rebels were not parties to the 
accords but the southwest african peoples organization said it 
would honor a ceasefire 
in washington president reagan said the agreements promise to 
end the cycle of violence which has plagued the namibianangolan 
border area for more than 13 years inflicting untold human misery 
and property damage 
under the agreement 3000 cuban soldiers are to leave angola by 
april 1 and all are to be gone by july 1 1991 it requires half the 
50000 troops to be withdrawn by nov 1 1989 when namibians vote 
for a national assembly under un supervision 
all the signatories have committed themselves to a sequence of 
steps necessary to achieve peace in southwestern africa and to open 
the way to independence for namibia perez de cuellar said after 
the main agreement was signed 
foreign ministers isidoro malmierca of cuba and afonso van dunem 
of angola then signed a pact stipulating that 70 un peacekeepers 
will monitor the cuban withdrawal 
anatoly adamishin soviet deputy foreign minister for african 
affairs also attended the ceremony he was an observer at the 
negotitions and is credited with urging cuba and angola to show more 
flexibility 
he said the kremlin is ready to continue to bring to bear all 
the authority of its policy and by practical deeds to work for the 
establishment of peace and tranquillity in this area 
malmierca said the united states and south africa were the source 
of conflict in the region 
botha speaking later said he was willing to join malmierca in a 
debate of cubas foreign and human rights policies lasting into 
the night 
shultz who presided at the ceremony ignored the cuban foreign 
ministers request that he be allowed to respond 
van dunem urged the united states to end its support for angolan 
rebels and grant his government diplomatic recognition 
if we are to fulfill our goals without prolonging any longer 
the suffering of the angolan people it is imperative there be no 
more meddling in angolas internal affairs he said 
implementing the agreements will require cooperation between 
angola and washington he said and such collaboration could 
surely be facilitated by the normalization of diplomatic relations 
south africa has controlled southwest africa a territory of 
about 12 million people that is rich in minerals since capturing 
it from germany in world war i the un general assembly revoked a 
league of nations mandate in 1966 but the south africans refused to 
leave 
</TEXT>
