the soviet union and china have bought more 
grain from the united states including wheat sold to beijing at 
subsidized prices the agriculture department said thursday 
moscows order was for an additional 1 million metric tons of 
corn for delivery under a recently extended supply agreement between 
the two countries the department announced china bought 400000 
tons of wheat under the subsidy program 
the latest sales by private exporting companies brought total 
corn sold to the soviets to almost 803 million tons in the 
agreements sixth year which began oct 1 last year us corn 
sales to the soviet union totaled slightly less than 52 million 
tons 
exporters are required to report foreign grain sales of 100000 
tons or more to the usda within 24 hours smaller sales are reported 
weekly 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 394 bushels 
of corn or 367 bushels of wheat or soybeans the 1 million tons of 
corn would be about 394 million bushels 
corn prices have been averaging about 261 per bushel at the 
farm level according to usda estimates meaning that the latest 
sale could have a farm value of around 103 million 
although no wheat has yet been sold for 198889 delivery under 
the pact the soviets have ordered 500000 tons of soybeans and 
532500 tons of soybean meal plus 500000 tons of grain sorghum 
melvin e sims general sales manager for the departments 
foreign agricultural service said seven export companies were 
involved in the sale of 400000 tons of wheat to china some 147 
million bushels having an estimated farm value of 58 million at 
recent prices 
the companies included cargill inc 90000 tons central states 
enterprises 40000 tons nissho iwai american corp 30000 tons 
bunge corp 40000 tons tradigrain inc 50000 tons tradecom 
inc 30000 tons and louis dreyfus corp 120000 tons 
sims said the sales were part of an authorized 1 million tons of 
wheat announced on dec 7 under the export enhancement program or 
eep with the latest sales china now has 210000 tons remaining 
under the authorization 
the program enables exporters to sell wheat and other designated 
commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in order to 
meet foreign competition the exporters then collect free government 
surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses or subsidies 
sims said the bonuses due the seven exporters for the latest deal 
averaged 2310 per ton of wheat or about 63 cents per bushel 
