<TEXT>
the us death rate from diabetes the nations 
seventhleading killer dropped sharply during the 1970s but seems 
to have stalled in recent years the centers for disease control 
said thursday 
the mortality rate from diabetes as the primary cause of death 
fell by an average of 4 percent each year from 1970 to 1979 from 
21 such deaths per 100000 people in 1970 to 149 nine years later 
the cdc said 
the number of deaths caused by diabetes dropped from 38324 in 
1970 to 33192 in 1979 
but in the following six years the mortality rate from diabetes 
fell only slightly to 147 per 100000 by 1985 the latest year for 
which data are available the number of deaths actually increased 
somewhat to 36969 
thats something we dont have an answer for said robert r 
german a cdc diabetes specialist after 1980 for some reason it 
appears to be leveling off 
the same pattern is evident in statistics on cases in which 
diabetes was part of the diagnosis but not necessarily the primary 
cause of death 
the rate of diabetesrelated deaths dropped from 757 per 100000 
people in 1970 to 577 in 1979 then went up to 591 by 1985 german 
said the number of deaths dropped from 137241 in 1970 to 128373 
in 1979 then went up again to 148284 in 1985 
were in the process of trying to determine what is going on 
german said 
overall the decline in mortality from diabetes may reflect two 
factors the cdc said a trend away from listing diabetes on death 
certificates or an actual decline as a result of improved treatment 
and longer survival for patients 
diabetes typically is present in older people in 1980 84 
percent of diabetes patients were 45 or older and 40 percent were 
65 or older the cdc said 
the cdc report concerns diabetes mellitus which is widely 
referred to simply as diabetes 
according to the american diabetes association more than 11 
million americans suffer from diabetes a disease caused by the 
bodys inability to produce or properly use insulin a hormone 
needed to convert sugar into energy 
complications from diabetes include blindness heart and kidney 
disease nerve damage and gangrene that can cause loss of limbs 
