<TEXT>
a federal judge on thursday struck down 
portions of a 1952 law allowing the government to deport aliens for 
espousing antiamerican beliefs saying the provisions violate 
immigrants freespeech rights 
us district judge stephen v wilson also threw out an exception 
to a 1987 law that recognized free speech rights for all immigrants 
in deportation proceedings but members of the palestine liberation 
organization 
wilson said congress already has passed a powerful array of laws 
dealing with terrorism and his decision would not significantly 
deplete the governments arsenal in combating terrorism 
the ruling came in a twoyearold case involving seven jordanians 
and a kenyan who were arrested held without bail and subjected to 
deportation proceedings under the mccarranwalter act a federal 
immigration judge released them and the government eventually 
dropped mccarranwalter proceedings against all but two although it 
sought deportation of the others on technical grounds 
a government attorney said wilsons ruling would be appealed 
wilson on struck down sections of the 1952 mccarranwalter act 
providing for deportation of an alien who advocates or is 
affiliated with a group that espouses world communism 
dictatorship or unlawful destruction of property 
the ideological provisions of the mccarranwalter act do not 
withstand first amendment analysis he said 
he said the mccarthyera statute was overbroad and could 
cause deportation for something as simple as wearing a political 
button 
he cited the landmark 1969 decision in brandenburg vs ohio in 
which the us supreme court held that the government can only 
prohibit speech directed toward inciting imminent lawless action 
the judge also ruled that the plo exception to the 1987 foreign 
relations authorization act violated guarantees of due process and 
equal protection under the law 
in this case the government is trying to stifle certain ideas 
from entering our society from certain aliens the judge said 
our society however was built on the premise that only through 
the free flow of ideas can our nation grow and prosper 
the arabamerican antidiscrimination committee had sued the 
justice department on behalf of the immigrants and the battle was 
joined by the american civil liberties union and the center for 
constitutional rights based in new york 
one of the original defendants khader hamide 34 called the 
decision a victory for arab and palestinian immigrants 
we feel as a community now we can speak our minds on the 
palestinian issue hamide said we can speak our minds on the 
uprising on the west bank and in gaza and express our opinions 
freely without the fear of being put in jail 
david cole of the center for constitutional rights said the 
judges ruling on the plo exception to the 1987 law means that 
congress cannot make politically motivated distinctions in 
providing first amendment rights to aliens 
paul hoffman of the aclu noting the governments decision to 
appeal said the case would most likely be decided by the us 
supreme court 
when it is decided i think it will be one of the handful of 
major first amendent cases that have ever come down in this 
countrys history he said 
