the gulf cooperation council ended a 
summit meeting thursday pledging to consolidate the iraniraq peace 
drive safeguard freedom of navigation in the persian gulf and seek 
an international conference on the palestinian question 
the six member nations endorsed saudisponsored talks between the 
soviet union and afghan rebels amid speculation that oil giant saudi 
arabia was moving toward resuming diplomatic ties with moscow after 
a 50year break 
attending the fourday summit were king fahd of saudi arabia 
sultan qaboos of oman sheik jaber alahmed alsabah of kuwait 
sheik khalifa bin hamad al thani of qatar sheik zayed bin sultan al 
nahyan of the united arab emirates and sheik isa bin salman al 
khalifa of bahrain 
they stressed their resolve to strengthen collective defense 
capabilities and boosted economic integration plans with a manama 
declaration calling for speededup efforts toward a gulf common 
market 
in a closing communique read by council secretarygeneral 
abdullah bishara of kuwait the group said it backed efforts by un 
secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar to promote a peace treaty 
between iran and iraq to formally end their 8yearold war iran and 
iraq agreed to a unsponsored ceasefire in august 
