<TEXT>
other labor leaders shun eric hammond and 
he rivals margaret thatcher as a hate figure for the left but many 
see the maverick union boss as a natural product of the prime 
ministers age of enterprise 
hammond is the polecat of organized labor particularly since his 
electricians union was expelled from the national labor federation 
and he appears to enjoy the role 
his eyes twinkle as he lauds laws that have emasculated the 
oncemighty labor movement since mrs thatcher and her conservative 
party won power in 1979 
im only halfjoking when i say well be erecting statues to 
the tories before the end of the century he said why because 
they will have saved the trade union movement from itself 
labor legislation in the thatcher decade has outlawed sympathy 
walkouts forced secretballot membership votes before strikes are 
called and empowered employers to sue unions for damages resulting 
from illegal strikes 
a revolution was wrought in british working practices and 
hammonds 360000member electrical electronic telecommunication 
and plumbing union joined it 
in his office at the unions elegant headquarters a converted 
mansion in commuter country 10 miles from london hammond continues 
the unionbaiting that got him banished from the trades union 
congress the 9 millionmember british labor federation 
he is accused of splitting organized labor making cozy nostrike 
deals with employers invading the territory of other unions and 
through a 1986 deal with publisher rupert murdoch to run his 
hightechnology presses breaking the power of newspaper production 
unions 
hammond 59 is a sharp contrast and constant provocation to 
leftwing leaders of old traditional unions arthur scargill and 
his national union of mineworkers for instance and the huge 
transport and general workers union with its 1250000 members 
hard times have been forced upon the unions and the way eric 
hammond has tried to solve this is through sweetheart deals with 
employers said andrew murray an official of the transport union 
a strike is always a weapon of last resort the question is 
whether union officials have the right to surrender that resort 
in september the trades union congress expelled hammonds 
electricians for refusing to abandon singleunion nostrike deals 
with a japanese electronics company in wales and a british food 
chain 
hammond unrepentant delivered his credo in a final speech to 
the federations annual conference and walked out before the 
expulsion vote was taken 
our members he thundered reveal an enthusiasm for the 
market system and its values and infuriate the sherryparty 
revolutionaries with their model resolutions and conferencehall 
rhetoric 
he is negotiating a merger with the amalgamated engineering 
union which has 800000 members and is the nations second largest 
after the transport workers 
if that goes through next year the trades union congress must 
either take the electricians back in their new form or risk the 
emergence of a rival federation of the highestskilled workers 
although hammond is isolated at least for now he sees himself 
as the smart kid on the block the adapter to modern realities in a 
bleak time for organized labor 
membership in unions belonging to the trades union congress has 
declined from nearly 13 million to under 9 million since 1979 
nearly 50 percent of british workers belonged to unions then but 
only 35 percent do now 
hammonds background is impeccably working class he is the son 
of a papermill timekeeper grew up in a modest home at gravesend 
20 miles east of london and became an apprentice electrician at 16 
he began as a leftist he said but moved right 
communists took over the union but were kicked out in a 1962 
ballotrigging scandal and the right has controlled it since frank 
chapple hammonds cockney predecessor was the scourge of the left 
in the socialist labor party which unions founded and finance 
chapple now a life peer sitting in the nonelected house of 
lords warned his many enemies in the tredes union congress when he 
retired four years ago you think im rightwing wait till you 
see eric 
experience bore him out 
hammond has excoriated the london labor party for as he put it 
consorting with terrorists lesbians and other queer folk 
he has pushed singleunion deals with or without nostrike 
clauses that stipulate binding arbritration 
unions have made more than 30 such arrangements mainly with 
japanese electronic companies often after several unions vie to 
offer managers the most attractive package 
hammonds alliance with murdoch revolutionized the newspaper 
industry in less than two years when murdoch fired 5000 production 
workers in january 1986 for striking against new hightech 
machinery hammond and his electricians moved in to run the presses 
with the production unions vanquished the rest of the national 
newspaper industry quickly followed suit 
the other unions were demanding jobs for life and murdoch 
said get lost hammond said in the interview i dont see how 
we could have acted any differently 
these deals are what our members want and thats what its all 
about membership were operating in a tough environment 
