<DOCNO> AP881222-0266 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the eec commission on thursday proposed 
legislation to harmonize the widely differing rules on corporate 
takeovers in the 12 european economic community nations 
under the legislation a company offering to buy more than a 
third of another firms shares must offer to buy all shares 
also a company initiating a takeover would have to state its 
intentions about a target companys future activities the fate of 
its work force and indebtedness 
the requirement on indebtedness would be important in cases 
involving a leveraged buyout in which the purchase is financed by 
the future debt of the target company 
the proposed legislation would also forbid company management 
from carrying out exceptional operations or share sales to block 
a takeover without the permission of their shareholders 
the legislation was proposed after months of intense debate on 
the issue at the eec head office it now goes to the 12 eec member 
states which may amend the proposed legislation 
one commission expert said the proposed legislation reflected a 
golden mean between the extensive takeover legislation in force 
in some eec nations and the lack of major guidelines in others 
britain has the eecs most developed takeover rules whereas 
corporate takeovers and legislation governing these are 
virtually nonexistent in denmark and greece 
the approach to takeover legislation varies considerably from one 
eec nation to the next 
france spain and portugal have a great deal of binding 
legislation while many guidelines in britain west germany italy 
the netherlands and ireland are voluntary codes the law in belgium 
and luxembourg is largely the product of accumulated precedents 
the commissions proposed uniform takeover regulations are part 
of its bid to create a singlemarket eec as of dec 31 1992 
it said unfiform guidelines are important as the number of 
takeovers is likely to rise in advance of 1992 and crossborder 
corporate relationships develop and intensify 
another commission proposal on merger and takeover policy which 
was discussed by eec trade ministers on wednesday is a separate 
move to prevent such actions from harming industrial competition 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0267 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
control data corp facing a breakeven 
year in 1988 says it told its 27000 us employees they must take 
five days off without pay in the first quarter of 1989 
that equates to a 78 percent pay cut in the first quarter or 
about 2 percent for the year frank ryan a spokesman for the 
computer company said wednesday executives will take an 
additional 5 percent pay cut over the first six months of 1989 he 
said 
in addition merit pay raises have been delayed three months and 
the company has canceled for the first six months of 1989 its policy 
of matching a portion of employee contributions to a company pretax 
savings plan the company had matched 25 percent of the first 2 
percent of an employees cash compensation ryan said the company 
wont say how much money these measures will save he said 
in a letter to employees notifying them of the cutbacks control 
data chairman robert price said they were necessary to regain our 
momentum by showing a profit in each quarter of 1989 ryan said 
if control datas financial position improves by the third quarter 
of 1989 employees will be repaid with as many as five extra paid 
days off ryan said 
the companys 7000 employees in other countries will not be 
affected by the cutbacks 
countries around the world have a variety of labor relations 
laws that make it difficult to implement this ryan said 
