<TEXT>
a group of 35 congressmen most of them from 
textile states has complained to top banking and security 
officials about farley incs unsolicited 14 billion bid for west 
pointpepperell inc claiming the proposed deal would weaken the 
nations battle against textile imports 
the letter to federal reserve chairman alan greenspan and 
securities and exchange commission chairman david ruder includes 
general worries about leveraged buyouts and also echoes pepperells 
specific charges that the bid is too heavily financed by debt 
among those who signed the letter sent this week are rep richard 
ray dga whose district includes pepperells headquarters in west 
point ga and rep henry gonzalez dtexas who will chair the 
house banking committee in the new congress 
meanwhile farley on thursday again extended its 48pershare 
offer until jan 4 the offer originally was made in october and 
has been extended past several expiration dates 
and pepperells board set a special shareholders meeting for feb 
25 at the meeting farley will attempt to replace current board 
members with its own nominees who would be expected to rescind 
pepperells antitakeover defenses 
leveraged buyouts in which acquisitions are financed with 
borrowed money secured by the targets cash flow or assets may be 
saddling corporations with a dangerous level of debt which will 
restrict their ability to modernize and to weather economic 
downturns the congressmens letter said 
the 1934 securities exchange act directed the federal reserve 
board to issue margin regulations to limit the excessive use of 
credit in securities transactions the letter said now more 
than ever congress expects the federal reserve board and the 
securities and exchange commission to assure that those margin 
regulations are enforced 
pepperell has filed suit trying to block farleys bid claiming 
among other things that the offer violates those regulations but a 
federal district judge ruled against the georgia company the case 
has been appealed to the 11th us circuit court of appeals which 
has set a jan 11 hearing date 
by any objective measure west pointpepperell is a growing and 
healthy company the letter says but farleys plans to break up 
the company after a takeover means we risk losing one of the 
strongest us competitors in the worlds textile market 
