<TEXT>
the final defendant in the giant washington public 
power supply system securitiesfraud trial has settled with 
classaction plaintiffs for 20 million an attorney said thursday 
the settlement by blyth eastman painewebber inc which had acted 
as a financial adviser to wppss was confirmed by blyth eastman 
attorney james hagan 
the end of the trial came nearly six years after the first 
lawsuit was filed in the giant legal action that grew from wppss 
default on 225 billion in bonds sold to finance two nuclear power 
plants the default was the biggest in the history of the municipal 
bond market and more than 25000 plaintiffs were involved 
thats the last defendant and thats the end of the trial 
hagan said by telephone from his new york office 
the securities fraud case was being heard by a federal judge in 
tucson ariz where it had been moved from washington state 
the settlement brought to about 700 million the total that more 
than 100 original defendants have agreed to pay plaintiffs in the 
trial another 50 million could be collected through contested 
insurance claims 
total claims by plaintiff bondholders were 16 billion though 
the default was on 225 billion worth of bonds 
the trial which started sept 7 before us district judge 
william browning was recessed dec 1 and had been scheduled to 
resume jan 9 however with the settlement browning was expected 
to dismiss the jurors 
the judge still must approve 16 separate settlements made over 
much of the past year four settlements agreed to as early as 
september 1987 have already been approved by browning 
attorneys said they hoped to get the notice of settlements to the 
class of plaintiffs by jan 16 and to get approval for all of them 
in a march hearing 
with several classes of plaintiffs as diverse as original bond 
buyers and those who purchased bonds at pennies on the dollar just 
weeks ago the judge must also decide how the money is to be 
divided those who have been close to the case have said it could 
still be a year or two before final payments are made to plaintiffs 
still to be extracted from the 700 million in settlements are 
fees for dozens of attorneys many of whom have worked on the case 
for five years without being paid attorneys who have been paid have 
collected more than 100 million separate from the settlements 
tens of millions of dollars have also been spent on everything 
from computerized systems to keep track of the massive amounts on 
data to remodeling the courtroom for the aborted trial 
defendants in the lawsuit which incorporated dozens of separate 
suits filed as early as feb 22 1983 in federal court in seattle 
included the supply system the 88 utilities that contracted with 
wppss to build the two plants engineering firms wall street bond 
underwriters utility and wppss directors and the advisory firm of 
blyth eastman 
the default was on bonds wppss sold to finance construction 
starting in the late 1970s on its plants no 4 at the hanford 
nuclear reservation and no 5 at satsop west of olympia 
wppss abandoned the plants in 1982 and default occurred in july 
1983 after the washington state supreme court ruled that utilities 
participating in construction of the plants lacked authority to sign 
contracts with wppss guaranteeing payment even if no electricity was 
generated 
