<TEXT>
treasury secretary pedro aspe flew to 
washington wednesday night for talks on mexicos 102 billion 
foreign debt the treasury department said 
aspe was to hold talks with us treasury secretarydesignate 
nicolas brady and with barber conable head of the world bank the 
department said in a brief statement 
mexicos new president carlos salinas de gortari wants debt 
payments cut so the stagnant mexican economy can begin growing again 
and has has made renegotiating the debt the second highest in the 
developing world after brazils a top priority 
aspe told congressmen last week that he hopes to persuade foreign 
creditors to reduce debt payments from the current level of about 5 
percent of the gross national product to about 3 percent 
he said salinas had sent a proposal to creditor banks in the 
united states and europe 
aspe did not disclose the details of the proposal but the mexico 
city financial daily el financiero said it would nearly halve the 
amount mexico expects to pay in 1989 and devote more of the payments 
to principal rather than interest 
debt payments amounted to about 14 billion in 1988 and are 
expected to reach 16 billion in 1989 
salinas said in his first budget last week that mexicos economy 
will begin growing again toward the end of 1989 after debt payments 
fall he predicted 15 percent growth in the gross national product 
nearly four times that of 1988 
mexico the worlds sixthlargest oil producer began 
accumulating its huge debt in a borrowing spree during the oil boom 
of the late 1970s when the bottom fell out of the international oil 
market in 1982 the mexican economy nosedived into a crisis that 
still grips the nation 
